<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1436,1289,2008]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1435,1460]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Description:</emphasis>
MALE (
<figureCitation box="[458,552,1436,1460]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="46.[151,244,1924,1945]" captionTargetBox="[255,1339,170,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-83@46.[236,1357,153,1915]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 5. Daedalma adults (left: dorsum, right: venter). A. inconspicua blancae Holotype ♂. Balzapamba; B. inconspicua onorei ♂ Holotype, Pilaló; C. inconspicua inconspicua ♂, via La Victoria; D. inconspicua inconspicua ♀, vía La Victoria; E. inconspicua variegata ♂ Paratype, Calacalí; F. inconspicua variegata ♀ Holotype, Cotacachi; G. inconspicua orientalis ♂ Holotype, Pondoa; H. inconspicua orientalis ♀ Paratype, Pondoa" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
): Head, thorax and abdomen: not differing from nominate subspecies. FW length: 
<quantity box="[236,339,1472,1496]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="26.5">26.5 mm</quantity>
. HWV without any reddish suffusion typical of nominate subspecies and 
<emphasis box="[1168,1275,1472,1496]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">orientalis</emphasis>
, dirty yellowish olive green patches slightly larger than in nominate. HWV ground colour lighter than in the nominate; light patches pale yellow, not cream-white of nominate, and more extensive than in the nominate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1197,1307,1545,1570]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1324,1423,1545,1569]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="52.[151,244,1958,1979]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,155,1946]" captionTargetId="figure-67@52.[228,1380,119,1970]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURE 11. Daedalma male genitalia (in lateral view, aedeagus removed from its natural position). A. dognini dognini, San Luis; B. dognini mirianae, Pillcopata; C. inconspicua blancae, Balzapamba; D. inconspicua onorei, Pilaló; E. inconspicua inconspicua, vía La Victoria; F. inonspicua variegata, Cotacachi" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 11F</figureCitation>
): Uncus stout, slightly arched, about same length as shoulder of tegumen; gnathos over 2/3 length of uncus; slightly longer than in nominate; saccus, valvae and aedeagus not differing from nominate subspecies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1436,1289,2008]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
FEMALE (
<figureCitation box="[328,415,1655,1679]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="46.[151,244,1924,1945]" captionTargetBox="[255,1339,170,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-83@46.[236,1357,153,1915]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 5. Daedalma adults (left: dorsum, right: venter). A. inconspicua blancae Holotype ♂. Balzapamba; B. inconspicua onorei ♂ Holotype, Pilaló; C. inconspicua inconspicua ♂, via La Victoria; D. inconspicua inconspicua ♀, vía La Victoria; E. inconspicua variegata ♂ Paratype, Calacalí; F. inconspicua variegata ♀ Holotype, Cotacachi; G. inconspicua orientalis ♂ Holotype, Pondoa; H. inconspicua orientalis ♀ Paratype, Pondoa" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 5F</figureCitation>
): Head, thorax and abdomen: not differing from nominate subspecies. Wings: FW length: 
<quantity box="[151,276,1691,1715]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="31.0" valueMax="32.0" valueMin="30.0">30–32 mm</quantity>
, mean: 
<quantity box="[368,451,1691,1715]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="31.0">31 mm</quantity>
, n=2; differs from other subspecies by extensive, light orange markings on FWD and HWD, covering most of distal half of wings, whereas nominate subspecies only shows some reddish scaling. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[227,326,1764,1788]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="57.[151,244,1823,1844]" captionTargetBox="[184,1419,207,1787]" captionTargetId="figure-53@57.[151,1436,191,1802]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 16. Daedalma female genitalia (1: ventral view, 2: lateral view). A. drusilla drusilla, Env. Bogotá; B. drusilla krugeriana, Albania; C. inconspicua variegata, Cotacachi; D. inconspicua inconspicua, vía La Victoria" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
): Ductus bursae bent ventrally, so that the long axis of corpus bursae points ventro-anteriorly, ventrally with a few pronounced transverse wrinkles. Antrum very short, colliculum well pronounced. In lateral view, the entire eighth segment elongated, its large lateral parts widely separating heavily sclerotized plates of tergite and sternite. Papillae anales with lobe-like extensions bearing setae on their edges that point toward each other. Outer walls of papillae anales opposite to base of rudimentary apophyses posteriores set off as bumps. Ventral surface of ninth segment with parallel anterio-posterior wrinkles. V-shaped batten on lamella postvaginalis well sclerotized, roundly bent in middle and pointing posteriorly. Lateral parts of antrum with few pronounced sclerotized wrinkles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,152,176]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Etymology</emphasis>
: The epithet of this subspecies, 
<emphasis box="[685,792,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">variegata</emphasis>
is Latin for 'colourful', and refers to the brightly coloured dorsal surface of the female.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,225,249]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks</emphasis>
: This subspecies is so far known only from the Volcán Cotacachi and Pululahua massifs, situated north-west of Quito on the western slopes of the Cordillera. The single male is associated with this subspecies based on known distribution patterns of high elevation 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pyrcz &amp; Gareca" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[767,911,297,321]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Pronophilina">Pronophilina</taxonomicName>
satyrines in this part of the Ecuadorian Andes. In several polytypic species, the populations occurring in Pululahua and Cotacachi areas belong to the same subspecies (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Staudinger" authorityYear="1888" box="[294,507,369,393]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Lymanopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nivea">
<emphasis box="[294,507,369,393]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Lymanopoda nivea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[529,787,369,393]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Daedalma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inconspicua">
<emphasis box="[529,787,369,393]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Daedalma inconspicua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not known to occur in the well-sampled area of western 
<collectingCountry box="[151,244,405,429]" name="Ecuador" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
north of the Río Mira valley (Pyrcz 
<emphasis box="[653,709,405,429]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">et al.</emphasis>
, 2009).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
